WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.170 --> 00:00:13.920
[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to talk about how our approach to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:20.840
arithmetic so far in this foundational series&nbsp;
for mathematics connects with primary school&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:28.200
mathematics education. Certainly, we do not want&nbsp;
primary school students learning mathematics in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:32.760
the way that I have been formulating it&nbsp;
in this series because that's meant for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.760 --> 00:00:38.960
a very mathematically mature audience. But&nbsp;
nevertheless, it gives us some good hints.

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:45.360
So let's start off with our first and most&nbsp;
important subject, the natural numbers. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:50.400
I've already emphasized before that there are&nbsp;
really three different levels at which we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:57.920
introduce natural numbers: first as strings&nbsp;
of ones, then in a sort of simplified Roman&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:04.440
system using Roman numerals (X's, C's,&nbsp;
and M's, and so on), and then finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:10.840
more sophisticatedly, the Hindu-Arabic notation&nbsp;
that we traditionally use. I think it's important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:16.240
to distinguish these different approaches&nbsp;
and to try to get very young students,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:23.280
perhaps preschool students, thinking in terms&nbsp;
of this representation of natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:31.200
rather than this. Students don't have to learn&nbsp;
one, two, three when they're three years old,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:40.880
but they can learn to represent a group of&nbsp;
objects by a string of ones. That's very natural.

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:45.320
Then we discuss the operations, the primary&nbsp;
operations of addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:52.600
and the secondary operations of subtraction and&nbsp;
division. I think one of the main points is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.600 --> 00:02:00.120
we really need students to have lots of practice&nbsp;
in making these operations. Calculators, I've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:07.320
mentioned a few times, are not required;&nbsp;
they're not even advised. Students should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:13.720
learn to do calculations in their heads and&nbsp;
on paper, and they should do lots of them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:18.960
The laws that these operations satisfy&nbsp;
need to be very clearly enunciated and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:28.120
they need to be justified even for primary school&nbsp;
education. Long division is certainly necessary;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:37.440
all students must learn how to long&nbsp;
divide. Finally, it's very natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:44.240
to give examples of arithmetic coming from&nbsp;
number theory and combinatorics. In this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:52.720
we enrich students' experience of mathematics and&nbsp;
prepare them for further work. So those are points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.720 --> 00:03:00.080
that I would suggest when we develop a curriculum&nbsp;
for natural numbers for primary school education.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:07.440
The most important subject in primary school&nbsp;
mathematics education is fractions. Fractions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:12.640
can be introduced in a number of ways,&nbsp;
and I think for primary school students,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:20.360
a really good way is to think about little squares&nbsp;
representing natural numbers. If we do that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:25.800
then the numbers one, two, and three are&nbsp;
represented by little strips of squares,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:33.280
and when we do it that way with a two-dimensional&nbsp;
aspect, then describing fractions becomes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:38.800
relatively simple and straightforward. So this&nbsp;
fraction, half, can be conveniently represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:46.320
by taking a half of one of these little squares,&nbsp;
or 2/3 by dividing it into three and taking 2/3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:52.440
Here, for example, are three squares that would&nbsp;
be the number three, and the number 3/2 would be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.440 --> 00:04:00.680
represented by that portion of that, and you can&nbsp;
see physically that that is equal to the three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:09.040
halves that we had there. I would generally&nbsp;
avoid the usual pie-type pictures where we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:16.680
divide a circle into equal numbers of pieces. The&nbsp;
reason is that it's actually very hard to divide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:24.440
a circle evenly into, say, seven pieces; even&nbsp;
theoretically, that's a very hard thing to do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:33.400
and I don't think it really corresponds as&nbsp;
well to intuition as a linear representation.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:38.240
Here's another way of connecting what we've been&nbsp;
talking about in terms of fractions with what you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:44.320
can do in primary school. Here's a part of the&nbsp;
Cartesian plane with seven in this direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:49.320
three in this direction. So that's the ordered&nbsp;
pair of 7 and 3, and we said that if you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:56.480
a fraction like 7/3, you could associate it&nbsp;
with this ordered pair (7,3) or also with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:05.160
line from the origin to that point. Now, the&nbsp;
squares that we were talking about up there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:12.360
can very happily be represented by a strip.&nbsp;
This strip right here lies above the x-axis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:19.040
one unit high. Our line representing 7/3&nbsp;
intersects that strip right at this point here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:24.200
and if we allow that to cut off a little&nbsp;
rectangle, then that is the rectangle that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:34.000
in this context corresponds to 7/3. So in this&nbsp;
way, fractions correspond to parts of this strip&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:40.600
which is one unit high, and that gives fractions&nbsp;
a pleasant two-dimensional context. It's also,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:45.920
again, important to explain how the&nbsp;
operations on fractions come from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:52.560
more simple and basic operations on&nbsp;
numbers. And to emphasize once again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:58.720
it's absolutely crucial that students have lots&nbsp;
of practice without any calculators in actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:06.600
performing operations with fractions. These form&nbsp;
the basis for all facility with algebra later on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:13.080
and even at the university level, we often see&nbsp;
students that just don't have enough facility with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.080 --> 00:06:19.920
arithmetic with fractions. So the primary school&nbsp;
level, that's the place where that has to be done.

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:24.440
After students gain some facility with&nbsp;
fractions, we can introduce integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:28.240
and I think it's quite reasonable&nbsp;
to use an integer number line in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:37.080
the standard way to represent the integers.&nbsp;
The rational numbers are much like fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:40.960
and I think it's better to think about them&nbsp;
in a two-dimensional context rather than in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:46.720
a one-dimensional context. So I prefer that you&nbsp;
do not think in terms of a rational number line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:52.880
but rather in terms of a rational number strip.&nbsp;
That's a strip that extends in both directions and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:59.520
is one unit high. In this way, a rational number&nbsp;
which is positive is represented by a rectangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:06.240
going off to the right, starting from zero, and&nbsp;
we can represent that very conveniently by not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:12.840
just putting the rectangle in but also showing&nbsp;
the line through the origin that is represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:20.560
by that (7,3) out there somewhere. So that's a&nbsp;
nice way of representing the rational number 7/3:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:31.360
by a rectangle of height 1 with 7/3 with a line&nbsp;
going from bottom left to top right. That way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:38.520
a negative rational number, for example, -5/4,&nbsp;
can be represented also by a square, but this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:48.840
time with a line going from bottom right to top&nbsp;
left, representing the line that goes to the -5/4.

00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:53.600
A few extra points: The decimal numbers,&nbsp;
which we have not yet introduced (we will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:59.880
talking about them later after we've done some&nbsp;
geometry), are generally a more advanced topic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:07.480
and somewhat less fundamental than fractions.&nbsp;
Students should learn fractions thoroughly before&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:13.000
they learn decimals, and I would recommend,&nbsp;
perhaps controversially, that decimals are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:22.400
not actually studied, at least not in depth,&nbsp;
until post-primary school. I would also like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.400 --> 00:08:29.600
to point out that one should stress the relative&nbsp;
importance of concepts. In my quick perusal of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:35.840
primary school mathematics materials, I often&nbsp;
find a sort of blanket coverage where there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:42.480
a lot of material, and it's not emphasized what&nbsp;
are actually the really main points. I think when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:48.280
we organize mathematics, it's important to say&nbsp;
what actually is important and what is primary,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:55.160
what is secondary, and what is less important.&nbsp;
So the objects that we've been talking about so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.160 --> 00:08:59.440
far are really of primary importance,&nbsp;
and they should play a central role.

00:09:00.560 --> 00:09:05.200
So those are just some of my ideas. I don't&nbsp;
say that they should be cast in stone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:11.560
but there are ways in which our discussion of&nbsp;
foundational mathematics can have some say into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:18.720
what primary school education might have in&nbsp;
it in the mathematics direction. We're almost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:25.600
now at a stage where we're going to move into&nbsp;
geometry, the next and second important aspect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:31.000
of mathematics. But before I do that, I would&nbsp;
like to say something about an alternate way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:38.800
of thinking about natural numbers, fractions, and&nbsp;
so on. I want to discuss the use of infinite sets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:44.120
in modern mathematics. I do not believe&nbsp;
in infinite sets, and in my next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.120 --> 00:09:49.400
I'm going to explain to you why and why&nbsp;
you shouldn't believe in them either. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.400 --> 00:10:00.480
hope you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening. [Music]

